article.description: Utah's Kim Smith could do no wrong as she scored 35 points and the Utes rolled past DePaul.
article.headline: DePaul can't come back in second half
article.story:
RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- Kim Smith scored 35 points and Utah closed
the first half with a scoring surge to beat DePaul 73-64 in the
opening round of the Midwest Regional on Sunday.

	   Smith, the Mountain West Conference player and rookie of the
year, had 23 points in the first half as the No. 8 seeded Utes
(24-6) advanced by shooting 50 percent.

	   Smith's point total set the single-game NCAA Tournament mark for
the Utes and was one off the school record of 36 set by Susana
Tauteoli in 1993.

	   Ninth-seeded DePaul (22-10), making its first NCAA appearance
since 1997, trailed 20-19 before Smith and Shona Thorburn took over
in the final 7:46 of the first half.

	   Smith began the 25-8 run with a layup, and added eight more
points during a two-minute span to finish the opening 20 minutes
9-for-12 from the field, including three 3-pointers.

	   After Smith's second 3-pointer gave Utah a 32-23 lead, Thorburn
sank two behind the arc in a 23-second span and added a 15-footer
for a 17-point lead as Utah made seven straight shots.

	   Smith's 3-pointer 24 seconds before the break gave Utah an
18-point halftime lead.

	   DePaul rallied behind a trapping press, closing to 59-54 with
4:31 left, but Thorburn and Smith sank two free throws each to push
the lead to nine and the Blue Demons couldn't convert down the
stretch against the nation's top defensive team.

	   Smith finished 11-for-16 from the field and 10-of-12 from the
foul line.

	   Thorburn added 20 points and 10 rebounds for Utah, while Khara
Smith led DePaul with 24 points and 11 rebounds off the bench.
